Objective
Verify that the ARP scanner correctly discovers all active hosts on the local subnet and returns their correct IP address and MAC address using ARP broadcast packets.

Test Code
 
# TC-01: Network Scan Test
# Tester  : Shashank Saini
# Purpose : Verify ARP scanner discovers all active hosts
# Run     : sudo python3 tests/test_scan.py
 
from scapy.all import ARP, Ether, srp
 
def test_scan(network):
    print("[*] Testing Scan Module...")
 
    arp    = ARP(pdst=network)
    ether  = Ether(dst="ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff")
    packet = ether / arp
 
    result = srp(packet, timeout=2, verbose=0)[0]
 
    if result:
        print("[+] Scan Working")
        for sent, received in result:
            print(f"{received.psrc} --> {received.hwsrc}")
    else:
        print("[-] No devices found or scan failed")
 
# Run test
test_scan("192.168.1.0/24")
 

How The Code Works — Step by Step
1.	ARP(pdst=network) — Creates an ARP "Who has?" request targeting every IP in the subnet range.
2.	Ether(dst="ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff") — Wraps ARP in an Ethernet broadcast frame so ALL devices on the network receive it.
3.	srp(packet, timeout=2) — Sends the packet at Layer 2 and collects replies from all devices that respond within 2 seconds.
4.	result loop — Each reply contains psrc (sender IP) and hwsrc (sender MAC). These are printed for verification.

